An exploratory data analysis of a chemical detection platform to predict the presence of CO(ppm) in its chamber.

¶
a work by:
Virginia Itzel Contreras Miranda
itzelvcm@gmail.com

This work presents an analysis of a real-life chemical detection platform that is exposed to a mixture of carbon monoxide (CO) and humid synthetic air in its gas chamber. The platform is composed of 14 temperature-modulated metal oxide semiconductor (MOX) gas sensors.

There are 13 datasets provided, each of them corresponds to a different measurement day. The datasets contain 20 variables:

  1. Time (s): experiment time
  2. CO concentration (ppm): its bottle contain1600 ppm of CO diluted in synthetic air with 21 1% O2.
  3. Humidity (%r.h.): it has a uniform distribution between 15% and 75% r.h. randomly chosen.
  4. Temperature (C): its variation is below 3C.
  5. Flow rate (mL/min): releases the gas mixtures at a 240 mln/min constant rate.
  6. Heater voltage (V): controls the operating temperature of the sensors and is modulated in the range of .2-.9.
  7. R1 (MOhm)
  8. R2 (MOhm)
  9. R3 (MOhm)
  10. R4 (MOhm)
  11. R5 (MOhm)
  12. R6 (MOhm)
  13. R7 (MOhm)
  14. R8 (MOhm)
  15. R9 (MOhm)
  16. R10 (MOhm)
  17. R11 (MOhm)
  18. R12 (MOhm)
  19. R13 (MOhm)
  20. R14 (MOhm)

In this work, an exploratory data analysis of the dataset is going to be made as well the evaluation of several machine learning algorithms that will be able to predict the presence of CO (ppm) in the gas chamber.

It is necessary to import all the packages that you need to develop your work.

Data cleaning¶

The first step of this analysis consists in import all the experiments made and concatenate them to have only one dataset instead of 13.

Every file contains the day and hour of when measurements started in their file names. It is necessary to assign the date of every individual dataset as an index or variable to have the possibility to make a different analysis as time series. In this case, the date is assigned in the index.

A for loop is implemented to assign the date for the 13 datasets and also to know if there are any missing or duplicated values in it. The analysis of the missing values is going to be individually by every dataset because if there is any, I would substitute those missing values by the mean of the column of such missing values on that specific date.

In this case, there are not any missing or duplicated values in any of the datasets, so now I'm able to concatenate them, finishing the data cleaning phase.
In [2]:
path = "/Users/itzelcontreras/Desktop/dataset tempMod CO_RH/"
all_files = glob.glob(os.path.join(path, "*.csv")) #make list of paths

i=0
d={}
fec={}


for file in all_files:
    # Getting the file name without extension.
     fec[i] = os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(file))[0]
        
    # Reading the file content to create a DataFrame.
     d[i] = pd.read_csv(file)
     d[i].drop(d[i].iloc[:, 20:40], inplace = True, axis = 1) 
    
    #Using the file name to know the date of the file.
     date_st= fec[i]
     format_st = '%Y%m%d_%H%M%S'
     dt = datetime.strptime(date_st, format_st)
     dat= dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

    #Assign the date to the index of the file.
     d[i]['Date']=dat
     d[i]['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(d[i]['Date'])
     d[i].set_index('Date', inplace=True)
 
    #Check if there is any missing and duplicated values. 
     dup= d[i].duplicated().sum()
     print("The dataset number %d has %d duplicated values and the following data corresponds to the number of missing values of every variable of the dataset:" % (i+1,dup))
     print(d[i].isna().sum())
     i+=1
 

    #concatenate all the files.
ds = pd.concat(d)
ds=ds.reset_index(level=0, drop=True)

It can be difficult to give an interpretation of the quantiles just with the numerical values, for that reason it is indispensable to graph a box plot for every variable of the dataset to see graphically the data distribution.

sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
x= 1 
f = 0
i= 6 #In this location of the dataset the first sensor starts.

#To graph more efficiently, a for loop is used. 
for f in range(3):    
    for x in range(4):    
        ax= sns.boxplot(ax=axes[x,f],x= ds.iloc[:,i]) 
        x+=1 
        i+=1
    f+=1    
x=0

#The last two graph boxes are not useful, so this for loop assign the last two sensors in the last column.
for x in range(2):    
    ax= sns.boxplot(ax=axes[x,3],x= ds.iloc[:,i]) 
    x+=1 
    i+=1

The resistance from R8 to 14 look very alike with an apparently normal distribution. In comparison with the resistance from R1 to R7 that corresponds from another distributor, the first three resistences show positive skewness, and the other four resistances have a normal distribution.

The variable time, CO, humidity, temperature, flow rate, and heater Voltage are graphed apart, because the range of every variable is quite different, so it was needed to graph every boxplot with its own y-axis.
In [6]:
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(14,4)})
df=ds.iloc[:,0:6]
selection = ['Time (s)','CO (ppm)', 'Humidity (%r.h.)','Temperature (C)','Flow rate (mL/min)','Heater voltage (V)']
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(selection))

#This for loop is is used to graph a variable in every iteration.
for j, col in enumerate(selection):
    ax = sns.boxplot(y=df[col], ax=axes.flatten()[j])
    ax.set_ylim(df[col].min(), df[col].max())
    ax.set_ylabel(col + ' / Unit')
fig.tight_layout()
The time, CO, and humidity have approximately equal proportions in all the quantiles. The temperature has some outliers and its distribution has negative skewness. The flow rate variable has as it's mean the constant released specify in the experimental protocol. The heater voltage variable maintains the limits recommended by the manufacturer.

A mean and standard deviation plot of the CO variable are going to be graphed to see how much the mean and standard deviation are changing over time.

In [7]:
#Size of the figures.
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(22,5)})
f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)

#Mean plot. 
sns.lineplot(x=ds.groupby(ds.index).mean().index,
             y=ds.groupby(ds.index).mean()['CO (ppm)'] , ax=axes[0] )
axes[0].set_title('CO (ppm) mean values',fontsize=20)

#Standard deviation plot.
sns.lineplot(x=ds.groupby(ds.index).mean().index,
             y=ds.groupby(ds.index).std()['CO (ppm)'] , ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title('CO (ppm) standard deviation values',fontsize=20)

plt.show()

The mean and standard deviation are very similar over time. On November the 10th the mean is higher so the standard deviation is low, which means most of the values are closer to the mean value.

A lag plot is presented. This graph allows us to check for the randomness and seasonality of our CO variable.

In [8]:
matplotlib_axes_logger.setLevel('ERROR')

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))

pd.plotting.lag_plot(ds.groupby(ds.index).mean()['CO (ppm)'], lag = 1)
plt.title("Lag CO plot", size=20)
plt.show()

The lag plot demonstrates that the variable CO hasn't any seasonality. I consider that the data is not randomness because almost all the data has a pattern, is concentrated almost in the same place in the graph.

A probability plot is made to visually compare the CO values with a normal distribution. It can be seen that it is really well distributed.

The scales of several variables of the dataset have a different range of values. For that reason, it is essential to normalize the data, in this case, the MinMaxScaler method it is applied. MinMaxScaler subtracts the minimum value in the feature and then divides by the range. The default range for the feature returned a value between 0 and 1. The MinMax Scaler is not going to be applied in the CO variable because your dependent variable does not necessarily need to be normally distributed.

Our dataset contains 20 variables. Sometimes when are too many attributes, it is no the best idea to include all of them in our machine learning model because some features can be irrelevant for the dependent variable. Feature selection helps in selecting the most appropriate variables of the dataset. The ANOVA F-value feature selection is used in this study. This feature selection method examines if, when we group the numerical feature by the dependent variable, the means for each group are significantly different.

def select_features(X_trainset, y_trainset, X_testset):
    
# Configure to select all features.
    fs = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=2)
    
# Learn relationship from training data.
    fs.fit(X_trainset, y_trainset)
# Transform train input data.
    X_trainset_fs = fs.transform(X_trainset)
    
# Transform test input data.
    X_testset_fs = fs.transform(X_testset)
    return X_trainset_fs, X_testset_fs, fs

The attributes with higher scores are from the R8 to the R14 resistance. Other relevant attributes are the time, humidity, and flow rate. It makes a lot of sense that the resistances (R8-R14) affect significantly the dependent variable because in the EDA section we demonstrate the high negative correlation between the CO and these 7 resistances.

These attributes are recommendations of the feature selection, so with this criteria, I am going to propose three variations of the dataset to analyze with every model:

  1. Dataset 1 = The original dataset with all the features
  2. Dataset 2 = 7 features of the original dataset (R8, R9, R10, R11, R12, R13, R14).
  3. Dataset 3 = 10 features of the original dataset (Time, humidity, flow rate, R8, R9, R10, R11, R12, R13, R14).

Three models are going to be used in this analysis:

  1. Linear regression: models the relationship between two variables by fitting a linear equation to observed data.

  2. Decision Tree: has a tree structure that breaks down a dataset into smaller subsets.

  3. Lasso regression: is a type of linear regression algorithm that penalizing the absolute size of the regression coefficients.

We need to split the dataset into train and test set, but instead of making just one split of the whole dataset, k-folds cross-validation is applied. The dataset is divided into k-folds, in this case, there will be 10. There will be 10 datasets and in ten iterations, all the datasets are going to be the train set nine times and the test set one time. As an example, in the first iteration, dataset #1 is going to be a test set, and the rest of the datasets are going to be the train. In the second iteration, dataset #2 is going to be the test set and the rest of the datasets, the train.

Three metrics are going to be evaluated:

  1. R-squared: represents how close the data are to the fitted regression line.

  2. Mean Squared Error (MSE): represents the average of the squared difference between the original and predicted values in the dataset. It measures the variance of the residuals.

  3. Mean absolute error (MAE): represents the average of the absolute difference between the actual and predicted values in the dataset.

The bigger the value of R-squared and the lower the value of MSE and MAE it is better.

Every model implemented is going to obtain 10 results per metric for the k-folds cross-validation implementation. I will obtain the mean of those ten results for every metric in all the models.
